i am writing a book about the 's any suggestions anything information i use will be credited any information names background suggestions so far i think it will be about a young womens life and how she lived and what she did a little research goes along way but not all people are great with research anyway i will give you some knowledge i know first is it going to be based on a american girl a girl coming to america or a native girl a slave girl that would help me give you some suggestions american girls boys life in the s was very different than now the girls and boys would have to go and do their chores at in the morning before they went to school many students went to school barefoot and in the same thing they wore the day before because most boys and girls had or two outfits one was for church the other one was for school and play they would wear them for up to three weeks when they got to school they would see their younger and older siblings and neighbors because the school taught children from grades one to eight most boys would only go to school for three or four months out of the year because during those other eight or nine months they would be helping their fathers in the fields some days there would be forty kids in school and other days there would be only five if you got in trouble the school marm or teacher would have you put your nose to the board wear a sign or hold books on your hands with your arms out the kids had an hour lunch and two recesses a day after school the school marm would go and spend the night at someone's house and would take them to school the next day some chores for boys were fetching water and chopping wood the girls would churn butter and grind corn the parents slept downstairs in a bed and the kids slept in the loft on the floor the fire was burning almost all day the blacksmith played a very important part in the town he would make hooks to hang and dry the food so it would last longer the would also use the hooks to hold pots over the fire Bristol Grammar School Recess (TV series) Comanche Boy Scouts of America Kodocha Shaggy dog story Billy the Kid Urinary incontinence The Catcher in the Rye Ned's Declassified School Survival Guide Boarding school About a Boy Westminster School Salad Fingers Hogwarts Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban Teachers (film) Boston Public Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Assonet, Massachusetts Japanese tea ceremony Hun-Apu Great Teacher Onizuka The Adventures of Pete & Pete Raffles Institution Graduate school Recurring South Park characters Education in Germany Child sexuality Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Situation comedy My Parents are Aliens New Morning W.I.T.C.H. The Shining (film) Butters Stotch Beavis and Butt-head No Child Left Behind Act Breath of Fire III Hunter College High School Odyssey Murdock-Portal Elementary School Pitaten Teen Girl Squad The Giver Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints Independent school (UK) Paul Is Dead One Tree Hill (TV series) John the Baptist French law on secularity and conspicuous religious symbols in schools Heber C. Kimball Poker jargon Darken Rahl King George V School Mattress Ramallah Static Shock Propaedeutic value of Esperanto Final Fantasy: Unlimited Taikyoku shogi The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe SpongeBob SquarePants Aerial (dance move) Humphrey Bogart Bethalto, Illinois Daylight saving time Rais massacre Barbecue Battles of Lexington and Concord Education in Romania Kimberly-Clark Corporation Kitchen The Family from One End Street Fecal incontinence EastEnders Sumo Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder One-room school Bart chalkboard gags Empire Burlesque The Jeffersons (South Park) Peanut Education in Scotland KaBlam! Firefighter Garfield Irish dance Happy Tree Friends Avenue Q Shawn Michaels 